```class Solution {
public:
    int racecar(int target) {
        int speed = 1;
        int position = 0;
        int count = 0;

        while (position < target) {
            if (speed > 0) {
                position += speed;
                speed *= 2;
            } else {
                speed = abs(speed);
                position += speed;
            }
            count++;
        }

        return count;
    }
};
```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(log(target))
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW

Explanation:

The algorithm uses a while loop to iterate until the car reaches the target position. Inside the loop, it checks the current speed and updates the position accordingly. If the speed is positive, it doubles the speed and adds the current position. If the speed is negative, it abs() the speed, changes its sign, and adds the current position. The loop continues until the car reaches the target position. The count variable keeps track of the number of instructions needed. The solution has a high efficiency because it uses a single loop and a few arithmetic operations. The time complexity is O(log(target)) because the loop stops as soon as the car reaches the target position. The space complexity is O(1) because the algorithm uses a constant amount of space for the count variable. The energy implications are low because the algorithm only performs arithmetic operations and does not involve any energy-consuming operations.

